<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Opaque" class="currentChild" href="Opaque">Opaque</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
When used as an adjective, <em>opaque</em> is descriptive of any substance or material that does not allow the transmission of light through it, or possesses a high degree of <a title="Opacity" href="Opacity">opacity</a>. The opposite of opaque is <a title="Transparent" href="Transparent">transparent</a>. A middle-ground is a <a title="Translucent" href="Translucent">translucent</a> substance or material, which allows some light to pass through it, albeit diffusely. 
</p>
<p id="l3">
The term <em>opaque</em>, when used as a verb, means to apply a thick fluid to portions of a photographic <a title="Negative" href="Negative">negative</a> prior to platemaking, as a means of eliminating unwanted images or specks, known as <a title="Opaquing" href="Opaquing">opaquing</a> or <a title="Spotting Out" href="Spotting_Out">spotting out</a>. 
</p>
<p id="l5">
The term <em>opaque</em>, when used as a noun, refers to the thick, typically red or black fluid used for blocking out the aforementioned undesirable specks or images on photographic negatives. Also known as <a title="Opaquing Fluid" href="Opaquing_Fluid">opaquing fluid</a>. A special red felt-tip markers used for the same purpose is also called <em>opaque</em>. 
</p>
